They will have the flexibility to turn themselves into all kinds of

00:13:01.590 --> 00:13:03.140
other institutions.

00:13:03.140 --> 00:13:09.240
And it's also a common understanding here that one entity running

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:13.980
the, running this thing alone is not what we want in

00:13:13.980 --> 00:13:15.110
the end.

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:17.260
It's a sort of starting point that we, that we

00:13:17.260 --> 00:13:18.070
can jump off from.

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:22.550
And if this kind of works, this identity system can be

00:13:22.550 --> 00:13:26.430
used by all other projects, by many other projects.

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:35.270
So I said the directory needs to do two things.

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:40.180
It needs to, and I will concentrate on this for the

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:41.960
rest of my time.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:46.260
It needs to decide whether an operation that's being submitted is

00:13:46.260 --> 00:13:47.220
a valid one.

00:13:48.740 --> 00:13:53.690
Valid in the sense of, does it match, does

00:13:53.710 --> 00:14:00.220
the signature match, does this all mathematically look okay?

00:14:00.220 --> 00:14:02.060
Yeah, that's one criteria.

00:14:02.060 --> 00:14:07.260
But if that stays the only criteria, I think we can

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:09.960
imagine what happens.

00:14:10.040 --> 00:14:16.720
Anyone can upload anything that matches these criteria to this public database

00:14:16.910 --> 00:14:17.180
.

00:14:17.260 --> 00:14:19.760
And the public database doesn't know, hey, is this

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:20.200
a DDoS?

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:21.240
Is this a spammer?

00:14:21.250 --> 00:14:21.860
I don't know.

00:14:21.860 --> 00:14:24.800
So basically, we're back to this Bitcoin problem.

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:28.720
And the common understanding is here that we want to avoid crypto

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:30.420
economics as much as we can.

00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:33.820
Because we know right now, so by now we have learned

00:14:33.820 --> 00:14:36.660
a little bit what the consequences are.

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:43.290
So we want to be able to devise robust ways to

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:50.390
distinguish whether this is a legitimate, in-good-fa

00:14:50.390 --> 00:14:53.560
ith request or whether this is an attack to the system.

00:14:57.560 --> 00:15:02.230
And the second thing that's important is it needs to serve

00:15:02.230 --> 00:15:04.070
the right history.

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:08.680
So sometimes, for some reasons, there may be not just

00:15:08.680 --> 00:15:11.670
appending to a DIT history, but a fork of

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:12.520
a DIT history.

00:15:12.620 --> 00:15:15.180
For example, when something, when some keys get compromised,

00:15:15.290 --> 00:15:21.950
and the directory could, in some situations, maybe if it

00:15:21.950 --> 00:15:26.180
's an adversary that runs the directory, could serve an older

00:15:26.180 --> 00:15:30.380
or a different branch of a DIT document history.

00:15:31.420 --> 00:15:34.130
And Edmund Edgar will talk about this problem, as far

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:35.880
as I understand, today at 5 p.

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:36.240
m.

00:15:36.240 --> 00:15:37.760
So check this out.

00:15:37.900 --> 00:15:41.100
I will only talk about this validity question here.

00:15:41.100 --> 00:15:44.910
One skeet that I want to quote here is from July

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:49.950
last year, where people are already looking at what kind of

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:55.020
operations are being stored in the current directory.

00:15:55.020 --> 00:15:57.960
And there was all kinds of nonsensical stuff being

00:15:57.960 --> 00:15:59.090
uploaded there.

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:05.380
So it turns out that the people who run this box currently

00:16:05.420 --> 00:16:11.480
have to keep the situation under control and clean stuff up.

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:14.710
And yeah, they, for good reason, want to get

00:16:14.780 --> 00:16:18.600
rid of this job responsibility as soon as possible.

00:16:21.620 --> 00:16:27.920
So, how can we design more robust systems?

00:16:27.920 --> 00:16:30.320
And one design methodology I'm very fond of, and I

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:33.320
think it's also the design methodology of the Blue Sky Project

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:36.480
, is called adversarial design.

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:40.680
So you assume that you're embedded in an adversarial environment

00:16:40.680 --> 00:16:43.940
, and the question is how to survive, in some sense

00:16:43.940 --> 00:16:44.210
.

00:16:44.620 --> 00:16:47.560
So, the adversarial design means you're always asking the

00:16:47.890 --> 00:16:50.820
question, what is the most efficient method to make the system

00:16:50.820 --> 00:16:52.490
less useful for key actors?

00:16:52.500 --> 00:16:56.400
You try to find and identify what would a rational actor do

00:16:56.400 --> 00:16:59.520
to make this unusable for the key persons?

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:07.440
And then use that input to develop defense mechanisms.

00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:09.980
And I think, currently, I'm trying to sort of

00:17:10.120 --> 00:17:13.630
finish this up and publish this a little bit better, because

00:17:13.630 --> 00:17:14.680
it's in the works.

00:17:14.680 --> 00:17:19.900
But currently, my main focus is, I believe that a

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:26.620
rational actor that's interested in making the PLC less usable

00:17:26.620 --> 00:17:30.490
, and less lightweight, and less easy to mirror and monitor

00:17:30.490 --> 00:17:30.720
.

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:35.440
So, like, an adversary would try to erode this

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:37.300
transparency.

00:17:37.300 --> 00:17:43.960
And I think the one brute force method that always will work

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:49.750
, is that the adversary creates a situation where it's almost

00:17:49.750 --> 00:17:52.480
impossible to distinguish valid from invalid requests.

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:55.430
So, there is no way of, currently, any IP

00:17:55.750 --> 00:17:59.500
address from anywhere can submit these requests.

00:17:59.500 --> 00:18:05.240
There is no metadata signal available that says, okay, this

00:18:05.240 --> 00:18:09.240
may be a useful request, or this is maybe a spam

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:11.500
attack, or a DDoS attack.

00:18:11.500 --> 00:18:14.800
Yeah, this is, the next graph is a little bit

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:17.620
, like, fresh from my documents.

00:18:17.620 --> 00:18:22.300
It says that, if, for example, if you say

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:26.820
, this is an ordered, so, like, this is

00:18:26.860 --> 00:18:31.930
the volume of requests, and the volume here means, at

00:18:31.930 --> 00:18:35.420
zero, it means that nothing indicates that they are inauth

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:36.020
entic.

00:18:36.020 --> 00:18:37.080
Everything seems fine.

00:18:37.080 --> 00:18:39.780
This looks like normal signups from normal PDSs,

00:18:39.780 --> 00:18:42.900
and then maybe there are indicators in the system that say,

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.800
okay, this is definitely something illegitimate, because it

00:18:45.820 --> 00:18:46.700
doesn't make sense.

00:18:46.700 --> 00:18:49.240
It's, we can rule it out as something, this

00:18:49.390 --> 00:18:50.240
is not valid.

00:18:50.240 --> 00:18:52.250
We know that, we know that this is not valid for

00:18:52.250 --> 00:18:52.640
sure.

00:18:52.660 --> 00:18:54.900
And if you, for example, order these cases, and

00:18:55.010 --> 00:18:57.420
you have this bottom in the middle, you can always say

00:18:57.420 --> 00:18:59.340
, oh, let's put the line of valid, invalid

00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:00.020
here.

00:19:00.020 --> 00:19:02.960
And then there is, there should be no fuss, no

00:19:03.290 --> 00:19:03.720
fight.

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:06.670
All the mirrors, all the witnesses would have the same understanding

00:19:06.990 --> 00:19:08.940
of valid and invalid, and we say, yeah, sure

00:19:08.960 --> 00:19:09.260
.

00:19:09.260 --> 00:19:12.200
This stuff definitely does not need to be stored in a public

00:19:12.540 --> 00:19:15.380
database, and this stuff definitely should.

00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:19.200
And I think an adversary will create this situation here.

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:24.150
This is a rough modeling of the expectation we have, that

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:28.370
the adversary will, in some sense, this would be the

00:19:28.370 --> 00:19:31.850
worst case, yeah, when everything looks as valid or invalid

00:19:31.850 --> 00:19:34.240
as everything else, then you have no chance of deciding.

00:19:35.040 --> 00:19:38.880
And this would be something where there are two minimas,

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:42.730
then if one group of mirrors or witnesses decides, okay,

00:19:42.820 --> 00:19:46.490
this is the one, and another group decides that this is

00:19:46.490 --> 00:19:49.400
the one, the system diverges, and it gets less

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:50.080
coherent.

00:19:50.580 --> 00:19:53.950
And then you have many PLC directories that are claiming

00:19:53.950 --> 00:19:57.060
different things or having subsets of entries.

00:19:57.060 --> 00:20:00.770
And this is really bad because then you cannot really rate limit

00:20:00.770 --> 00:20:03.540
in the rest of the system anymore, I think.

00:20:03.540 --> 00:20:04.820
It's hard.

00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:07.760
It's very hard to rate limit at the relay ingestion

00:20:08.100 --> 00:20:10.970
, I think, if you don't have a clear overview

00:20:10.970 --> 00:20:13.540
of who is part of this and who is not.

00:20:15.120 --> 00:20:18.070
And then, I think I have, yeah, nine minutes

00:20:18.390 --> 00:20:20.060
left, which is plentiful.

00:20:20.080 --> 00:20:22.850
I want to keep some minutes for questions.

00:20:22.860 --> 00:20:26.380
Maybe the last few slides, I would like to talk about

00:20:26.380 --> 00:20:30.550
the role of academic institutions, because I am working now for

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:31.080
one.

00:20:31.540 --> 00:20:35.240
And I have witnessed so many discussions about whether ActivityP

00:20:35.240 --> 00:20:37.180
ub or AT-Proto or NOSTER or anything

00:20:37.260 --> 00:20:38.860
else is now the way to go.

00:20:38.860 --> 00:20:42.290
I think this is a discussion that needs to happen as soon

00:20:42.290 --> 00:20:44.540
and as coherent as we can have it.

00:20:44.560 --> 00:20:49.500
I think institutions, science institutions need to come together and find

00:20:49.590 --> 00:20:55.400
a rough consensus, because I also think they have a role

00:20:55.400 --> 00:21:00.760
they need to embody here, because they are still kind of

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:01.620
trusted.

00:21:01.620 --> 00:21:05.530
In most parts of Western society, academic institutions are not seen

00:21:05.530 --> 00:21:09.520
as kind of completely treacherous organizations or something like that

00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:09.830
.

00:21:09.900 --> 00:21:13.390
But they are still holding this public trust, in a sense

00:21:13.390 --> 00:21:16.950
, and I think it would be extremely cheap and extremely on

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:22.210
-brand if they invest in monitoring and witnessing PLC infrastructure

00:21:22.300 --> 00:21:22.660
.

00:21:22.660 --> 00:21:25.610
I'm not so sure about who should do the proof of

00:21:25.930 --> 00:21:28.820
personal data station if we ever need one.

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:34.360
That means you need some kind of indication that you're really

00:21:34.360 --> 00:21:38.720
a human conscious person that is not trying to sign up and

00:21:38.720 --> 00:21:41.610
not a malicious AI swarm network.

00:21:41.700 --> 00:21:45.420
So, I think this proof of personal should not be done

00:21:45.420 --> 00:21:49.600
by the university currently, but I think this should be done

00:21:49.730 --> 00:21:51.340
by the university.

00:21:51.580 --> 00:21:54.530
And for that reason, Torsten, who is in the

00:21:54.860 --> 00:21:57.770
room, I think, maybe, and me, we tried

00:21:57.770 --> 00:22:03.550
to start a discussion within academia about a strategic cooperation between AT

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:07.200
-Proto and ActivityPub, which is aimed

00:22:07.240 --> 00:22:11.930
for convincing or just getting to a really, really broad consensus

00:22:11.930 --> 00:22:18.070
within the science community, which kind of protocol combination and identity

00:22:18.070 --> 00:22:22.730
, shared identity system we want to use in the academic world

00:22:22.730 --> 00:22:23.010
.

00:22:23.020 --> 00:22:25.520
So, if you want to, this is just the draft

00:22:25.710 --> 00:22:28.100
that was done in a couple of days here.

